οὐ ποιητής.] Οὐ is used even in classical Greek after εἰ, when, as here, it may be considered to coalesce with the particular word or phrase to which it is joined, and not to affect the condition generally (this takes place most easily with such words as θέλω or ἐάω), or when the negative conception is immediately contrasted with its positive, as below iii. 2 πολλὰ πταίομεν ἅπαντες. εἴ τις οὗ πταίει, 01· When it may be regarded as parenthetical, being most exactly represented by the insertion of such a phrase as ‘I do not say.' The same rule applies where the con- dition is assumed to be the fact, εἷ being equivalent to ἐπεί or ὅτι. But beside these cases, in which οὗ was admissible in classical Greek, the later Greek employs εἰ οὐ instead of εἰ μή as more emphatic, the latter being generally used without a verb (out of ninety-three examples cited by Bruder only fourteen are followed by a verb) in the sense of ‘ but’ or ‘ except.’ Of εἰ οὐ Bruder cites thirty-one examples, omitting how- ever this verse and iii. 2. On the other hand, μή is always used with
